2026 Regular Session ENROLLED
SENATE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION NO. 60
BY SENATOR EDMONDS
A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION
To designate Wednesday, May 6, 2026, as Recreation and Parks Association Day at the
Louisiana State Capitol and to designate the month of May as Recreation and Parks
Month in the state of Louisiana.
WHEREAS, the Louisiana Recreation and Parks Association's theme for Recreation
and Parks Month is "Build Together, Play Together"; and
WHEREAS, parks and recreation are essential to Louisiana's local communities
because they promote health and wellness, support childhood development, drive economic
opportunities, provide space for people to connect and socialize, and provide adaptable
infrastructure for resiliency in the face of natural disasters and climate change; and
WHEREAS, local parks departments across the state provide families with space to
gather and make memories, opportunities to introduce children to sports and nature, and a
variety of recreational activities; these parks provide Louisianians with a place to enjoy the
state's natural outdoor beauty, exercise, and take in fresh air; and
WHEREAS, recreation and parks help to grow a community's economic prosperity
by increasing property values, expanding the local tax base, generating tourism, attracting
and retaining businesses, and reducing crime; and
WHEREAS, local parks play a fundamental role in promoting the environmental
well-being of Louisiana communities through the conservation of wildlife habitats and
native flora, and also provide green infrastructure to mitigate the effects of localized
flooding; and
WHEREAS, two park systems in Louisiana are part of the less than two percent of
American park systems that have received accreditation through the National Recreation and
Park Association: the New Orleans Recreation Development Commission and the capital
region's Recreation and Park Commission for the Parish of East Baton Rouge (BREC); and
WHEREAS, local recreation and parks departments from across Louisiana will join
the Louisiana Recreation and Parks Association in gathering at the Louisiana State Capitol
to promote the vital role they play in local communities.
